# docker-restore.info

This file lists all available user command options for restoring containers/images using the docker-restore system.

## Main CLI Options

- `-show-backup-containers`   Show containers saved in backup JSON and recent restore log
- `-full-uninstall`           Remove all deployment traces: scripts, symlinks, systemd units, autoscript data (CAUTION: destructive)
- `-clean-field`              Stop/remove all containers, prune networks/volumes (CAUTION: destructive)
- `-image-capture-no-run`     Capture backup image (no restore)
- `-run-restore`              Run the restore process (requires stopped autostart service)
- `-m-restore`                Manual restore preview (dry run, no changes)
- `-restart-container <name>` Restart a specific container by name or ID
- `-restart-all`              Restart all stopped containers (with failsafe restore)
- `-json-now`                 Restore all containers/images from backup JSON immediately
- `-stop-autostart`           Stop the docker-autostart service
- `-resume-autostart`         Resume the docker-autostart service
- `-h, --help`                Show help message

## Failsafe Restore
If all restart attempts fail, the system will automatically attempt a full restore from backup JSON using native Docker.

## Usage Examples

- Show backup contents:
  `sudo docker-restore -show-backup-containers`

- Restore all containers:
  `sudo docker-restore -run-restore`

- Manual restore preview:
  `sudo docker-restore -m-restore`

- Restart all containers (with failsafe):
  `sudo docker-restore -restart-all`

- Restore from JSON directly:
  `sudo docker-restore -json-now`

## Notes
- All commands require sudo/root privileges.
- For best results, ensure Docker Desktop or native Docker is running.
- Backup JSON and image tars must exist in `/usr/autoscript`.
